00:00:21.970 --> 00:00:24.790
DENNIS FREEMAN:
So today the idea

00:00:24.790 --> 00:00:27.880
is to think about CT systems
in exactly the same way

00:00:27.880 --> 00:00:31.852
that we thought about
DT systems last time.

00:00:31.852 --> 00:00:33.310
For the past couple
of weeks, we've

00:00:33.310 --> 00:00:36.320
been looking at many
representations of both CT

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:37.360
and DT systems.

00:00:37.360 --> 00:00:42.250
Last lecture we made a picture
of a bunch of different ways

00:00:42.250 --> 00:00:43.960
to think about DT
systems and we tried

00:00:43.960 --> 00:00:47.610
to think about
relations between them.

00:00:47.610 --> 00:00:49.690
The new thing from
last time was this idea

00:00:49.690 --> 00:00:53.200
of a z transform, which formally
is the link between a system

00:00:53.200 --> 00:00:56.380
function, a function
of z, and a unit sample

00:00:56.380 --> 00:01:00.849
response, a function of n.

00:01:00.849 --> 00:01:02.640
We showed last time
that because we already

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:04.800
understand a whole lot of
these other connections

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:08.292
that connection is
very straightforward.

00:01:08.292 --> 00:01:10.000
What we're going to
do today is precisely

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.150
the same thing for CT.

00:01:13.150 --> 00:01:15.559
The boxes barely changed.

00:01:15.559 --> 00:01:17.350
You should see the
relationship immediately

00:01:17.350 --> 00:01:19.600
between the former set of
boxes and this set of boxes.

00:01:23.200 --> 00:01:25.750
And we'll do a
very similar thing.

00:01:25.750 --> 00:01:27.790
We'll look at a relationship
between the system

00:01:27.790 --> 00:01:30.280
function, which is
a function of s,

00:01:30.280 --> 00:01:33.820
and the impulse response,
which is a function of t.

00:01:33.820 --> 00:01:35.980
We'll look at that
similar function for CT,

00:01:35.980 --> 00:01:39.100
the thing that's analogous
to the z transform in DT.

00:01:39.100 --> 00:01:42.790
So Laplace transform,
just like in DT

00:01:42.790 --> 00:01:45.360
where it maps a function
of time to a function of z,

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:48.790
here it maps a function
of time, which in CT we'll

00:01:48.790 --> 00:01:49.840
write that way.

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:54.100
It maps that to a function of s.

00:01:54.100 --> 00:02:01.564
So s is going to be
something like x of t

00:02:01.564 --> 00:02:04.500
e to the minus st dt.

00:02:04.500 --> 00:02:07.000
So the idea is going to be that
this was a function of time.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:08.465
This is only a function of s.

00:02:08.465 --> 00:02:10.090
We get the function
of s by integrating

00:02:10.090 --> 00:02:12.610
some function of time,
but we integrate time out

00:02:12.610 --> 00:02:14.390
so time disappears.

00:02:14.390 --> 00:02:15.820
So the idea then
is that we end up

00:02:15.820 --> 00:02:21.940
with a map linking a function
of time to a function of s.

00:02:21.940 --> 00:02:24.080
Presumably you've
seen this before.

00:02:24.080 --> 00:02:27.860
This is a topic in 1803.

00:02:27.860 --> 00:02:29.060
Smile.

00:02:29.060 --> 00:02:29.900
Nod your head.

00:02:29.900 --> 00:02:32.090
Make me feel like I'm
connecting to you, right.

00:02:32.090 --> 00:02:33.960
Right, so you've all
seen this before.

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:35.180
Nothing's new.

00:02:35.180 --> 00:02:37.640
Actually there is one
tiny thing that's new.

00:02:37.640 --> 00:02:39.770
In 1803 they use a
variant of the Laplace

00:02:39.770 --> 00:02:42.800
transform that we will
call the unilateral Laplace

00:02:42.800 --> 00:02:45.485
transform, which means they
started their integrals at 0.

00:02:47.990 --> 00:02:50.930
For reasons that will be clear
at the very end of the course,

00:02:50.930 --> 00:02:55.200
when we do Fourier
transforms to make

00:02:55.200 --> 00:02:57.840
the transition between this kind
of a transform and a Fourier

00:02:57.840 --> 00:03:01.200
transform easier we
will do something

00:03:01.200 --> 00:03:03.930
called a bilateral transform.

00:03:03.930 --> 00:03:06.540
The only difference being that
we will start our integrals

00:03:06.540 --> 00:03:09.040
at minus infinity.

00:03:09.040 --> 00:03:13.650
There are subtle differences
between those two transforms.

00:03:13.650 --> 00:03:18.360
Rest assured, that the
big picture is identical.

00:03:18.360 --> 00:03:20.880
And when there is an
important difference

00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:23.740
we will point that out.

00:03:23.740 --> 00:03:27.030
So for the rest of today and
for the rest of two weeks

00:03:27.030 --> 00:03:29.910
I will only talk about
bilateral transforms, the kind

00:03:29.910 --> 00:03:31.710
that we integrate
over all of time.

00:03:34.602 --> 00:03:36.310
And the easiest way
I know to get started

00:03:36.310 --> 00:03:38.050
is to just try some, right.

00:03:38.050 --> 00:03:40.570
You could study
properties of the math.

00:03:40.570 --> 00:03:42.750
That's probably the way
it was studied in 1803.

00:03:42.750 --> 00:03:47.700
I find it easier to develop some
intuition for what's going on

00:03:47.700 --> 00:03:50.760
here by just doing some.

00:03:50.760 --> 00:03:52.500
So here's probably
the simplest Laplace

00:03:52.500 --> 00:03:55.140
transform we'll look at.

00:03:55.140 --> 00:03:59.220
What's the Laplace transform
of a function of time

00:03:59.220 --> 00:04:02.370
that exponentially decays
with positive time in a 0

00:04:02.370 --> 00:04:06.000
for time less than 0?

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:09.000
As you might expect, the
first transform we'll do

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:12.420
involve simply plugging
that mathematical formula

00:04:12.420 --> 00:04:14.890
into the definition.

00:04:14.890 --> 00:04:18.240
So the x of s, the
Laplace transform,

00:04:18.240 --> 00:04:20.910
is always the function of
time integrated against e

00:04:20.910 --> 00:04:23.370
to the minus st.

00:04:23.370 --> 00:04:25.680
We're only doing
bilateral but notice

00:04:25.680 --> 00:04:29.460
that the 0 for t less than
0 cuts off the bottom.

00:04:29.460 --> 00:04:31.230
So in fact, you would
get the same answer

00:04:31.230 --> 00:04:35.760
if you did bilateral
or unilateral.

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:40.170
And then we're left with
running this integral

00:04:40.170 --> 00:04:43.950
over infinite time this kind
of a function, which comes out

00:04:43.950 --> 00:04:45.880
looking like this.

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:49.650
The only tricky thing is
thinking about the implications

00:04:49.650 --> 00:04:53.080
of that infinity thing.

00:04:53.080 --> 00:04:56.550
There's going to be certain
values of s for which

00:04:56.550 --> 00:05:00.180
that integral diverges.

00:05:00.180 --> 00:05:03.140
So to think about that,
think about the thing

00:05:03.140 --> 00:05:04.480
that we're integrating.

00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:09.480
We're integrating something
that looks like e to the pt.

00:05:09.480 --> 00:05:12.620
We're integrating
against some function.

00:05:12.620 --> 00:05:16.240
So define the original function
of time is e to the minus t,

00:05:16.240 --> 00:05:17.990
here we have e to the
minus st. Let's just

00:05:17.990 --> 00:05:22.970
focus on that one for a
moment, the e to the st thing.

00:05:22.970 --> 00:05:25.280
We're going to generally be
worried about values of s,

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:28.550
or here, values of p,
that have complex values.

00:05:28.550 --> 00:05:30.800
We're going to be looking
at the s plane just the same

00:05:30.800 --> 00:05:32.665
as last time we
looked at the z plane.

00:05:32.665 --> 00:05:34.790
So we're going to think
about this thing might have

00:05:34.790 --> 00:05:36.155
a real and imaginary component.

00:05:36.155 --> 00:05:38.155
So we might have something
like looks like this.

00:05:41.860 --> 00:05:45.280
Sigma would be the
real part of p.

00:05:45.280 --> 00:05:48.790
Omega would be the
imaginary part of p.

00:05:48.790 --> 00:05:52.420
And somebody want
to hazard a guess

00:05:52.420 --> 00:05:55.720
at what that might look
like if I tried to expand it

00:05:55.720 --> 00:05:58.880
as a real and imaginary part?

00:05:58.880 --> 00:06:01.360
Someone wanted to hazard
a guess at the name

00:06:01.360 --> 00:06:02.920
of the equation I might use?

00:06:05.430 --> 00:06:06.760
AUDIENCE: Euler.

00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:08.700
DENNIS FREEMAN:
Euler's equation, sure.

00:06:08.700 --> 00:06:10.500
So I would expand this
by Euler's equation

00:06:10.500 --> 00:06:12.840
and I get something of
the form e to the sigma t,

00:06:12.840 --> 00:06:17.460
cos omega t plus j sine omega t.

00:06:20.547 --> 00:06:22.880
The point of writing
that out is that I

00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:25.220
hope it's clear that
convergence of the integral

00:06:25.220 --> 00:06:29.765
is going to depend critically on
the real or the imaginary part?

00:06:29.765 --> 00:06:32.890
Real, right?

00:06:32.890 --> 00:06:35.169
So the convergence is going
to be determined by this.

00:06:35.169 --> 00:06:37.210
This is the thing that's
affecting the magnitude.

00:06:37.210 --> 00:06:39.251
That's the thing that's
getting smaller or bigger

00:06:39.251 --> 00:06:42.980
as I go to infinity
or minus infinity.

00:06:42.980 --> 00:06:48.330
The cosine term, the sine
term, those are oscillating.

00:06:48.330 --> 00:06:53.460
They don't make the function
be more or less convergent

00:06:53.460 --> 00:06:55.867
than it was or originally.

00:06:55.867 --> 00:06:57.450
So when I'm thinking
about convergence

00:06:57.450 --> 00:07:00.240
I'm going to be thinking
about the real part.

00:07:00.240 --> 00:07:04.320
So over here if I want to
make this integral converge

00:07:04.320 --> 00:07:07.305
I want to be thinking about
t going from 0 to infinity.

00:07:07.305 --> 00:07:08.730
Well, 0 is not a problem.

00:07:08.730 --> 00:07:11.530
e to the 0 is 1,
that's going to work.

00:07:11.530 --> 00:07:13.420
It's the infinity
part that's a problem.

00:07:13.420 --> 00:07:17.160
So if I have infinity
plugged in for t,

00:07:17.160 --> 00:07:21.060
what's the range of values for
s for plus 1 that makes sense?

00:07:21.060 --> 00:07:24.300
That's the important
question, right.

00:07:24.300 --> 00:07:26.010
So I'm going to
want to constrain

00:07:26.010 --> 00:07:31.770
the real part of that number,
s plus 1, to be bigger than 0.

00:07:31.770 --> 00:07:34.320
If the real part of that
number is bigger than 0,

00:07:34.320 --> 00:07:36.300
then this thing
will converge to 0.

00:07:39.560 --> 00:07:42.180
If that converges to 0 then
I have a simple answer,

00:07:42.180 --> 00:07:43.940
it's just the answer
in the bottom.

00:07:43.940 --> 00:07:46.190
It's in the bottom so I have
to put a minus sign, that

00:07:46.190 --> 00:07:47.340
kills that minus sign.

00:07:47.340 --> 00:07:50.000
So my answer is 1 over s plus 1.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:51.230
Easy, right?

00:07:51.230 --> 00:07:54.680
And we will say that the Laplace
transform has a functional

00:07:54.680 --> 00:07:56.322
form, 1 over s plus 1.

00:07:56.322 --> 00:07:58.280
And it has region of
convergence, the real part

00:07:58.280 --> 00:07:59.485
of s bigger then minus 1.

00:07:59.485 --> 00:08:02.030
Just solving that inequality
for the real part of s so

00:08:02.030 --> 00:08:04.190
I can draw it on an s plane.

00:08:04.190 --> 00:08:06.590
So we'll associate
then with this

00:08:06.590 --> 00:08:11.480
s transform a picture which we
will commonly call the pole 0

00:08:11.480 --> 00:08:12.630
pattern.

00:08:12.630 --> 00:08:16.350
Is just a picture
of the s plane which

00:08:16.350 --> 00:08:20.890
shows me the singularities, the
poles and zeroes of the Laplace

00:08:20.890 --> 00:08:23.469
transform and the
region of convergence.

00:08:23.469 --> 00:08:24.510
So there's a single pole.

00:08:24.510 --> 00:08:27.110
There's a pole at
s equals a minus 1,

00:08:27.110 --> 00:08:29.940
so I indicate that by the x.

00:08:29.940 --> 00:08:32.880
And I have region of convergence
which I'll illustrate here

00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:35.650
with the gray area.

00:08:35.650 --> 00:08:39.480
So it converges for all values
of s that are in the gray area.

00:08:39.480 --> 00:08:41.010
OK, easy right?

00:08:41.010 --> 00:08:43.140
Trivial.

00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:46.400
OK, so now you get to
talk to your neighbor.

00:08:46.400 --> 00:08:47.700
OK, turn to your neighbor.

00:08:47.700 --> 00:08:49.110
Say, hi.

00:08:49.110 --> 00:08:51.030
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:08:51.030 --> 00:08:53.190
And figure out the
Laplace transform

00:08:53.190 --> 00:08:56.090
of a slightly more, but not
very complicated, function.

00:09:01.080 --> 00:09:04.573
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:10:53.060 --> 00:10:54.999
DENNIS FREEMAN: So
what's the answer?

00:10:54.999 --> 00:10:57.290
Everybody raise your hands,
show some number of fingers

00:10:57.290 --> 00:11:01.700
equal to the number of
the correct solution.

00:11:01.700 --> 00:11:04.620
Wonderful.

00:11:04.620 --> 00:11:08.000
The universal answer-- I think
it was universal-- was 1.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:09.210
So how do you get 1?

00:11:09.210 --> 00:11:12.057
What do I do?

00:11:12.057 --> 00:11:14.390
How do I find the Laplace
transform of the top function?

00:11:14.390 --> 00:11:17.680
[INAUDIBLE]

00:11:21.450 --> 00:11:22.900
DENNIS FREEMAN: Precisely.

00:11:22.900 --> 00:11:27.060
So what I do is just stick it
in the formula, do it twice.

00:11:27.060 --> 00:11:30.030
Laplace transform, like
the z transform, is linear.

00:11:30.030 --> 00:11:32.400
It will turn out that
the Laplace of a sum

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:33.585
is the sum of the Laplaces.

00:11:39.190 --> 00:11:44.142
If I simply stick the expression
for x2 into the definition,

00:11:44.142 --> 00:11:45.725
you can see it splits
into two pieces.

00:11:48.320 --> 00:11:50.090
And I get two parts.

00:11:50.090 --> 00:11:52.520
1 over s plus 1
just like I got--

00:11:52.520 --> 00:11:56.820
so the first part looks just
like x1, the first example.

00:11:56.820 --> 00:11:58.340
The second one looks
almost the same

00:11:58.340 --> 00:12:00.980
except there's a 2 where
there used to be 1.

00:12:00.980 --> 00:12:06.050
Shockingly, it changes
one of the ones into a 2.

00:12:06.050 --> 00:12:09.570
And then the only issue is where
is the region of convergence.

00:12:09.570 --> 00:12:13.160
So this part converges
if the real part of s

00:12:13.160 --> 00:12:15.758
is bigger than minus 1.

00:12:15.758 --> 00:12:21.030
This converges if the real part
of s is bigger than minus 2.

00:12:21.030 --> 00:12:22.950
So they both converge
if the real part of s

00:12:22.950 --> 00:12:24.740
is bigger than minus?

00:12:24.740 --> 00:12:26.000
AUDIENCE: 1.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:29.110
DENNIS FREEMAN: 1, right.

00:12:29.110 --> 00:12:32.680
If I'm in the region of s
where both the first part

00:12:32.680 --> 00:12:37.449
and the second part
converges then I'm fine.

00:12:37.449 --> 00:12:38.990
So that was all very
straightforward.

00:12:38.990 --> 00:12:44.020
I get an answer that
was number one, OK.

00:12:44.020 --> 00:12:48.050
So the transform is just
the sum of those two pieces.

00:12:48.050 --> 00:12:49.750
And the region is the
region of overlap.

00:12:54.450 --> 00:12:55.980
A more interesting
case, and where

00:12:55.980 --> 00:12:57.390
things are a little
bit different when

00:12:57.390 --> 00:12:59.306
we think about the
bilateral Laplace transform

00:12:59.306 --> 00:13:01.890
than unilateral,
is that the regions

00:13:01.890 --> 00:13:05.850
can be more complicated.

00:13:05.850 --> 00:13:12.020
So here's an example where
I've got a backwards traveling

00:13:12.020 --> 00:13:13.710
function.

00:13:13.710 --> 00:13:15.980
So now the function only
exists for t less than 0.

00:13:20.059 --> 00:13:22.100
As you might expect, just
stick it in the formula

00:13:22.100 --> 00:13:24.240
and see what happens.

00:13:24.240 --> 00:13:27.800
So stick this
expression into here.

00:13:27.800 --> 00:13:32.580
Now it lips off the
top of the integral.

00:13:32.580 --> 00:13:34.330
But when you're grinding
through integrals

00:13:34.330 --> 00:13:35.880
it's hard to tell
the difference.

00:13:35.880 --> 00:13:39.090
You get something that
looks very much the same.

00:13:39.090 --> 00:13:41.730
The thing that is different,
notice that the function

00:13:41.730 --> 00:13:42.960
was upside down.

00:13:42.960 --> 00:13:45.720
It was minus something
rather than plus something

00:13:45.720 --> 00:13:48.600
like the first example was.

00:13:48.600 --> 00:13:52.110
So the first example was e to
the minus t, t bigger than 0.

00:13:52.110 --> 00:13:55.470
This example is minus e to
the minus t, t less than 0.

00:13:58.540 --> 00:14:05.700
That gave me a minus sign
here but the nontrivial limit

00:14:05.700 --> 00:14:08.001
is at the top rather
than at the bottom.

00:14:08.001 --> 00:14:09.750
That's the reason I
put the minus sign in.

00:14:09.750 --> 00:14:11.333
So it would kill the
other minus sign.

00:14:14.180 --> 00:14:20.530
Also, since I need convergence
at t equals minus infinity,

00:14:20.530 --> 00:14:23.870
the region flips.

00:14:23.870 --> 00:14:27.830
I still need to have
that sort of thing decay

00:14:27.830 --> 00:14:30.920
so that the integral exists.

00:14:30.920 --> 00:14:34.620
But now the functions
are flipped in time.

00:14:34.620 --> 00:14:40.920
So the important range
of s is now flipped.

00:14:40.920 --> 00:14:46.980
So now I get the same functional
form exactly, but a region

00:14:46.980 --> 00:14:50.119
that's on the other side.

00:14:50.119 --> 00:14:51.660
That's one of the
central differences

00:14:51.660 --> 00:14:57.560
between the bilateral and
the unilateral transform.

00:14:57.560 --> 00:14:59.540
I need to tell you the
region of convergence

00:14:59.540 --> 00:15:02.572
for you to know which
of those two functions

00:15:02.572 --> 00:15:03.530
that I'm talking about.

00:15:07.400 --> 00:15:10.260
OK, so the important
thing from this example

00:15:10.260 --> 00:15:13.920
is the functional form
looks exactly the same.

00:15:13.920 --> 00:15:16.290
I had a functional form
in time, e to the minus t,

00:15:16.290 --> 00:15:18.390
e to the minus t.

00:15:18.390 --> 00:15:21.000
It was that functional
form of time

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:24.132
that I crank through
the integration for,

00:15:24.132 --> 00:15:25.590
and it's not
surprising then that I

00:15:25.590 --> 00:15:29.762
get a functional form for the s
transform that looks the same.

00:15:29.762 --> 00:15:31.720
If you start with functional
forms in time that

00:15:31.720 --> 00:15:34.875
look the same, you get
functional forms in s

00:15:34.875 --> 00:15:37.160
that look the same.

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:40.420
However, since the
region of t was

00:15:40.420 --> 00:15:45.990
different for the two functions
the region of s is different.

00:15:45.990 --> 00:15:47.400
There's also the negative sign.

00:15:47.400 --> 00:15:52.190
There's the fact that
this flipped this way,

00:15:52.190 --> 00:15:55.220
