about the two by two matrix.

00:35:23.830 --> 00:35:24.996
That's not the way it works.

00:35:29.460 --> 00:35:32.880
OK, two last things.

00:35:32.880 --> 00:35:34.230
First last thing.

00:35:34.230 --> 00:35:35.850
Probably the most
important thing

00:35:35.850 --> 00:35:38.250
about the Laplace transform,
probably the only reason

00:35:38.250 --> 00:35:41.190
we bother with that whatever
is that you can use it to solve

00:35:41.190 --> 00:35:42.810
differential equations.

00:35:42.810 --> 00:35:45.420
That's probably the
most important reason

00:35:45.420 --> 00:35:47.010
for even talking about it.

00:35:47.010 --> 00:35:49.600
The fact that we can take
it is of zero consequence.

00:35:49.600 --> 00:35:52.052
We can take lots of integrals.

00:35:52.052 --> 00:35:53.760
The interesting thing
about this integral

00:35:53.760 --> 00:35:57.360
is that it helps us to solve
differential equations.

00:35:57.360 --> 00:36:01.020
And the trick is that if we
start with the differential

00:36:01.020 --> 00:36:03.504
equation we can take
the Laplace transform

00:36:03.504 --> 00:36:04.920
of the whole
differential equation

00:36:04.920 --> 00:36:07.260
and that will end
up making sense.

00:36:07.260 --> 00:36:12.050
Just like the z transform, the
Laplace transform is linear.

00:36:12.050 --> 00:36:13.710
The Laplace
transform of a sum is

00:36:13.710 --> 00:36:16.020
sum of the Laplace transforms.

00:36:16.020 --> 00:36:18.660
That's pretty simple just
by looking at the definition

00:36:18.660 --> 00:36:22.380
because we can distribute the
e to the minus st over a sum,

00:36:22.380 --> 00:36:26.280
if x were a sum it distributes.

00:36:26.280 --> 00:36:27.790
So that's easy.

00:36:27.790 --> 00:36:30.750
The other important
thing is the derivative.

00:36:30.750 --> 00:36:33.210
What's the Laplace
transform of a derivative?

00:36:33.210 --> 00:36:35.250
That turns out to be easy.

00:36:35.250 --> 00:36:38.160
If that weren't easy, we
wouldn't even bother with it.

00:36:38.160 --> 00:36:40.390
But it is easy.

00:36:40.390 --> 00:36:43.020
You can see that if we
make the assumption that x

00:36:43.020 --> 00:36:48.190
is the Laplace transform
of x, and then if we define

00:36:48.190 --> 00:36:50.170
y is the derivative
of x, we can ask

00:36:50.170 --> 00:36:51.944
what's the Laplace
transform of y

00:36:51.944 --> 00:36:53.610
and that will tell
us what's the Laplace

00:36:53.610 --> 00:36:57.420
transform of the derivative.

00:36:57.420 --> 00:36:58.950
Take the definition
of transform,

00:36:58.950 --> 00:37:04.910
stick in y equals x dot
and integrate by parts.

00:37:04.910 --> 00:37:07.400
You all can integrate
by parts much better

00:37:07.400 --> 00:37:12.650
than I can because I
took it 35 years ago.

00:37:12.650 --> 00:37:18.195
But it's very easy to see that
if we call this u and this v

00:37:18.195 --> 00:37:23.240
dot, integral u dv is uv
minus the integral v du.

00:37:26.240 --> 00:37:29.030
The trick is that taking
integrals and derivatives

00:37:29.030 --> 00:37:34.180
of this part is easy,
it's an exponential.

00:37:34.180 --> 00:37:37.150
Exponentials are
the one function

00:37:37.150 --> 00:37:40.510
whose derivative has the
same shape as the function.

00:37:40.510 --> 00:37:43.800
That's the reason it's easy.

00:37:43.800 --> 00:37:50.300
So that means that I can
easily integrate that part.

00:37:50.300 --> 00:37:51.960
I can easily
differentiate that part

00:37:51.960 --> 00:37:54.626
to get something that looks just
like this, except as multiplied

00:37:54.626 --> 00:37:55.370
by minus s.

00:37:58.250 --> 00:37:59.810
And that minus s
is the only thing

00:37:59.810 --> 00:38:02.570
that ends up being important.

00:38:02.570 --> 00:38:05.450
The Laplace transform
of the derivative

00:38:05.450 --> 00:38:10.980
is s times the Laplace transform
of the original function.

00:38:10.980 --> 00:38:14.090
OK, differentiating
time is the same

00:38:14.090 --> 00:38:18.350
as multiplying by s in
a Laplace transform.

00:38:18.350 --> 00:38:20.900
Because of that it's
trivial to think

00:38:20.900 --> 00:38:26.050
about the Laplace transform
of a differential equation.

00:38:26.050 --> 00:38:28.720
Linearity says you
can do it term wise.

00:38:28.720 --> 00:38:30.610
And a differential
equation is something

00:38:30.610 --> 00:38:32.500
that has a bunch of
derivatives in it.

00:38:32.500 --> 00:38:35.170
Those all turn
into multiply by s.

00:38:35.170 --> 00:38:37.990
So you end up then with
this differential equation

00:38:37.990 --> 00:38:39.175
being replaced by this.

00:38:45.360 --> 00:38:49.810
So the Laplace transform of
the derivative is s times y.

00:38:49.810 --> 00:38:52.240
The Laplace transform of y is y.

00:38:52.240 --> 00:38:55.530
Now I have to figure out the
Laplace transform of delta.

00:38:55.530 --> 00:38:59.037
OK, turns out that's easy.

00:38:59.037 --> 00:39:00.620
What's the Laplace
transform of delta?

00:39:00.620 --> 00:39:02.630
That's why we like
delta functions.

00:39:02.630 --> 00:39:04.580
Delta functions seem
mathematically bizarre

00:39:04.580 --> 00:39:06.530
but they're so
easy to work with,

00:39:06.530 --> 00:39:08.990
that's the only
reason we use them.

00:39:08.990 --> 00:39:11.180
If you think about the
Laplace transform of delta

00:39:11.180 --> 00:39:13.760
just stick it in the formula.

00:39:13.760 --> 00:39:15.830
The interesting thing
about the delta function

00:39:15.830 --> 00:39:20.950
is that it's 0
almost everywhere.

00:39:20.950 --> 00:39:23.040
So we don't need to
worry about the product

00:39:23.040 --> 00:39:25.080
except where the delta
function is not 0.

00:39:28.250 --> 00:39:32.740
Because the delta function
makes the time axis mostly 0.

00:39:32.740 --> 00:39:36.540
The only place
that's not 0 is 0.

00:39:36.540 --> 00:39:39.690
So the only value of this
function that matters

00:39:39.690 --> 00:39:44.437
in the least is its value at 0.

00:39:44.437 --> 00:39:46.770
If you think about what that
looks like is as a picture.

00:39:50.340 --> 00:39:55.730
So if we have something that
looks like e to the minus st

00:39:55.730 --> 00:39:59.480
and if we multiply
by an impulse.

00:39:59.480 --> 00:40:01.260
The impulse is 0 except at 0.

00:40:01.260 --> 00:40:03.260
The only thing that
survives that multiplication

00:40:03.260 --> 00:40:08.360
is the value of e to the
minus st at t equals 0.

00:40:08.360 --> 00:40:10.280
We can think about
that as a limit.

00:40:10.280 --> 00:40:12.290
We thought about
the delta function

00:40:12.290 --> 00:40:16.010
as a limit of a function that
looks like this, minus epsilon,

00:40:16.010 --> 00:40:18.770
epsilon t, 1 over 2 epsilon.

00:40:18.770 --> 00:40:22.820
So that the limit as epsilon
goes to 0 becomes a delta.

00:40:22.820 --> 00:40:26.060
That's how we defined
the impulse function.

00:40:26.060 --> 00:40:28.430
If we think about that
definition in terms

00:40:28.430 --> 00:40:32.300
of this product you
can see that you

00:40:32.300 --> 00:40:36.270
get exactly this expression.

00:40:36.270 --> 00:40:41.510
So if you multiply this
times this all you pick out

00:40:41.510 --> 00:40:42.330
is this part.

00:40:45.800 --> 00:40:48.410
As you make epsilon smaller,
and smaller, and smaller,

00:40:48.410 --> 00:40:52.262
you focus just on
that point right at 0.

00:40:52.262 --> 00:40:53.470
The area of the impulse is 1.

00:40:53.470 --> 00:40:58.880
Therefore, the integral of
this thing is everywhere 1.

00:40:58.880 --> 00:41:00.530
So this sifts out.

00:41:00.530 --> 00:41:01.710
That's what we'll call it.

00:41:01.710 --> 00:41:03.335
So this is called
the sifting property.

00:41:08.130 --> 00:41:11.370
It's the nice part about
the delta function.

00:41:11.370 --> 00:41:13.500
If you integrate a
function with regard

00:41:13.500 --> 00:41:18.110
to time where the function
is multiplied by delta,

00:41:18.110 --> 00:41:20.600
that integral is the value
of the function at 0.

00:41:20.600 --> 00:41:23.840
It sifts out the 0 value.

00:41:23.840 --> 00:41:27.260
That means that the Laplace
transform of the delta function

00:41:27.260 --> 00:41:29.370
is 1.

00:41:29.370 --> 00:41:31.830
It's the most simple
function you can imagine.

00:41:31.830 --> 00:41:35.330
So the net effect of that
is that this differential

00:41:35.330 --> 00:41:38.690
equation, the Laplace transform
of the differential equation

00:41:38.690 --> 00:41:40.565
becomes an algebraic equation.

00:41:45.400 --> 00:41:49.050
That means that we can
solve it by doing algebra.

00:41:49.050 --> 00:41:52.500
So in particular, we can
readily solve the equation

00:41:52.500 --> 00:41:54.830
to find an expression for y.

00:41:54.830 --> 00:41:57.530
We saw that previously.

00:41:57.530 --> 00:41:59.720
We recognize ys.

00:41:59.720 --> 00:42:01.580
It's a recognition thing.

00:42:01.580 --> 00:42:03.950
It's a table look
up sort of thing.

00:42:03.950 --> 00:42:09.110
We know the form
1 over s plus 1.

00:42:09.110 --> 00:42:11.150
So we know the time
function that is the answer.

00:42:13.670 --> 00:42:15.440
So notice that when
we do this just

00:42:15.440 --> 00:42:17.390
the way that happened
with the z transform.

00:42:17.390 --> 00:42:18.950
When we solve a
differential equation

00:42:18.950 --> 00:42:22.190
by using Laplace transform we
basically don't use calculus.

00:42:24.662 --> 00:42:26.870
We use the Laplace transform
to turn the differential

00:42:26.870 --> 00:42:30.620
equation which is calculus in
1803 and that kind of stuff,

00:42:30.620 --> 00:42:33.200
into algebra, which
is high school.

00:42:33.200 --> 00:42:35.060
We do everything with algebra.

00:42:35.060 --> 00:42:39.014
The only annoying thing is
this table look up thing.

00:42:39.014 --> 00:42:40.430
It's a little
annoying that we had

00:42:40.430 --> 00:42:46.975
to do the inverse Laplace
transform by table look up.

00:42:46.975 --> 00:42:50.410
It's a little dissatisfying.

00:42:50.410 --> 00:42:55.630
So I'll just mention that
there is a formal way of not

00:42:55.630 --> 00:42:57.220
doing table look up.

00:42:59.656 --> 00:43:01.030
For the kinds of
problems we will

00:43:01.030 --> 00:43:03.910
look at using this
formula is so much more

00:43:03.910 --> 00:43:07.880
difficult than table look
up that we will never

00:43:07.880 --> 00:43:11.240
use that formula.

00:43:11.240 --> 00:43:13.160
It will be useful
for proving things,

00:43:13.160 --> 00:43:16.496
it will not be useful
for inverting things.

00:43:16.496 --> 00:43:17.870
Because of the
form of the things

00:43:17.870 --> 00:43:19.640
we do, linear
differential equations

00:43:19.640 --> 00:43:22.010
with constant coefficients,
it will always

00:43:22.010 --> 00:43:23.960
be easier to do
table look up then

00:43:23.960 --> 00:43:25.970
it will be to run this integral.

00:43:25.970 --> 00:43:29.247
If you're interested in that
integral, fine, take 1804.

00:43:29.247 --> 00:43:30.830
There's a bunch of
people who know all

00:43:30.830 --> 00:43:33.000
about how that integral works.

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:37.320
It's spectacularly interesting
but we won't use it here.

00:43:37.320 --> 00:43:42.020
So the upshot then is that
the Laplace transform,

00:43:42.020 --> 00:43:47.840
we learn about it
because it's very useful

00:43:47.840 --> 00:43:53.110
and its utility comes from
a bunch of properties.

00:43:53.110 --> 00:43:55.600
The ones we illustrated
today, we use the fact

00:43:55.600 --> 00:43:58.990
that it was linear
and we use the fact

00:43:58.990 --> 00:44:00.550
that there's a
simple relationship

00:44:00.550 --> 00:44:02.590
with differentiation.

00:44:02.590 --> 00:44:05.470
Using just those facts
it turns out easy

00:44:05.470 --> 00:44:09.550
to do differential equations
using the Laplace transform.

00:44:09.550 --> 00:44:11.290
And there's many
other things I've

00:44:11.290 --> 00:44:12.850
illustrated in the
last two slides

00:44:12.850 --> 00:44:16.360
but I won't go over
them right now.

00:44:16.360 --> 00:44:20.860
The idea of taking limits
using Laplace transforms.

00:44:20.860 --> 00:44:22.990
It turns out that the
Laplace transform is what

00:44:22.990 --> 00:44:25.880
we call a reciprocal function.

00:44:25.880 --> 00:44:29.695
Since the integrand depends
and the product of s and t,

00:44:29.695 --> 00:44:33.950
s gets large, corresponds
to t gets small.

00:44:33.950 --> 00:44:37.570
So you can take the
limit for things

00:44:37.570 --> 00:44:41.900
with time getting small by
looking at s getting big.

00:44:41.900 --> 00:44:44.530
Similarly, you can
do the reverse.

00:44:44.530 --> 00:44:48.490
You can look at time gets big
by looking at s gets small.

00:44:48.490 --> 00:44:50.876
That's just properties
of the Laplace transform.

00:44:50.876 --> 00:44:52.000
And there's lots of others.

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:54.670
Besides the table there's
lots of properties

00:44:54.670 --> 00:44:56.920
we won't have time
to go over but I

00:44:56.920 --> 00:44:58.060
will hint at some of them.

00:44:58.060 --> 00:45:00.880
And in particular, there's
a very useful transformation

00:45:00.880 --> 00:45:02.990
where you take the Laplace
transform of a circuit.

00:45:02.990 --> 00:45:05.720
And that's in the homework.

00:45:05.720 --> 00:45:08.540
So that's extremely useful.

00:45:08.540 --> 00:45:11.099
The major point then
is just that there's

00:45:11.099 --> 00:45:12.890
lots of relationships,
there's lots of ways

00:45:12.890 --> 00:45:14.370
we think about CT systems.

00:45:14.370 --> 00:45:17.480
This Laplace
transform is a new one

00:45:17.480 --> 00:45:22.360
and it's very useful because of
the properties in that table.

00:45:22.360 --> 00:45:24.470
OK, thanks a lot.

